4 ) Government policies to conserve water

Central Government Policies :

• National Water Mission (NWM) : Part of the National Action Plan on

Climate Change, this mission aims to conserve water, minimize wastage, and ensure

equitable distribution . It focuses on increasing water use efficiency by 20 % and

promoting integrated water resources management 1 .

• Atal Bhujal Yojana (ABY) : This scheme aims to improve groundwater

management through community participation . It focuses on sustainable

groundwater management in water - stressed areas 2 .

• Pradhan Mantri Krishi Sinchayee Yojana (PMKSY) : Launched to

improve irrigation efficiency, this scheme promotes micro - irrigation techniques

like drip and sprinkler systems to ensure 'more crop per drop’ 3 .

• AMRUT (Atal Mission for Rejuvenation and Urban

Transformation) 2 . 0 : This mission aims to ensure universal coverage of water

supply in all statutory towns and make cities 'water secure’ 3 .

• Jal Jeevan Mission (JJM) : Implemented by various states, this mission aims

to provide safe and adequate drinking water through individual household tap

connections by 20242 .

POLICIES TO CONSERVE

5) STATE GOVERNMENT

WATER

• State Water Policy 2022

The State Water Policy 2022 focuses on utilizing surface water to ensure

adequate water supplies . It includes measures to collect surface water from

rivers and other sources, and to collect excess water during floods for future use .

The policy also addresses issues like overexploitation of groundwater and

contamination of water sources 1 .

• Jalamrutha

Launched in 2019 , Jalamrutha is a major water conservation scheme aimed at

drought - proofing measures, including the protection and rejuvenation of water

bodies . It focuses on community - driven water conservation efforts 2 .

• Bengaluru Water Crisis Measures

To tackle the acute water crisis in Bengaluru, the government has allocated ₹ 556

crore . Measures include regulating water supply, banning the use of potable

water for non - essential purposes, and mandatory installation of aerators in taps

to reduce water consumption 34 .

• Cauvery V Stage Project

This project aims to provide piped drinking water to 110 villages added to the

city administration . It is expected to significantly increase the water supply to

Bengaluru 3 .

6) Plan of action

We decided to give awareness among people about water conservation, reuse of water

for various purposes, and better use of available water. We used the slogan:

Every drop of water counts, make every drop of water o matter.

Which says every single drop of water we use is precious. We gave awareness among

people by saying conserve water for sustainable future. We also explained the

importance of water conservation, different ways of saving water, and controlling the

water pollution. We tried to understand how much amount of water a person uses in

their daily life. Also we advised the people about rain harvesting, use of grey water

etc...

What we learned

The Theme Park has working models of recharge wells that visitors can see. An open

landscape can be put to use from a water conservation perspective. This will help

prevent soil erosion and allow water to infiltrate into the ground. The Theme Park has

models of infiltration trenches, check bunds, permeable pavers, etc

9 ) What we conveyed To people

We also conveyed the importance of rain water harvesting to people . As these people

were living in houses roof - top houses and terraced houses where these houses were

suitable for implementing rainwater harvesting system .

Rain water harvesting is simple and effective

way to conserve water as we can collect

rainwater from our roof - tops or terraces and store it in tanks .

We filter and clean this water to make safe for us to use . We use this water for irrigation,

washing cars, flushing toilets etc ...

We advised them to install rain water harvesting systems to conserve water.

Step 1: Install a tank or barrel to store water.

Step 2: Connect your downspout to the tank.

Step 3: Use filter to clean water.

By promoting awareness of rain water harvesting systems we can make positive impact

on environment.

1g. Creating awareness about rainwater harvesting at houses

11) What we Conveyed to people

We also researched about the amount of water usage by the people in their daily lives .

As many were not aware about the amount of water they use per day . While few said

the approximate values of water they use in their daily lives like 50 to 150 liters . The

amount of water used by one person in a day can vary depending on factors like

lifestyle, climate, and personal habits . According to the Indian government's

guidelines, a person should use around 135 liters of water per day for domestic

purposes . This includes :

- Drinking: 5 liters

- Cooking: 10 liters

- Bathing: 30 liters

- Toilet flushing: 20 liters

- Washing clothes : 20 liters

- Cleaning and other purposes : 50 liters

In urban areas, the average water usage per person per day is around 150 - 200 liters,

while in rural areas it's around 50 - 100 liters . The Indian government has also set targets

to reduce water usage to 100 liters per person per day by 2030 , as part of its water

conservation efforts .

1h,i - creating awareness about daily usage of water and conservation

12

Conclusion

In conclusion, the water conservation is a collective responsibility that requires immediate

attention and action . Every small step counts, and making conscious choices in our daily lives

can significantly impact the future of our planet . Remember, water is not just a resource, but a

lifeline .

Let's pledge to:

- Conserve water in every possible way

- Reduce our water footprint

- Protect our water sources

- Educate others about water conservation

- Support water - saving initiatives

Together, we can make a difference and ensure a water - secure future for generations to come.

Save water, save life!
